<subSubSection id="BE8AEB98FF9D4144FF3C262C4B29FE4F" pageId="7" pageNumber="408" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="F62FB813FF9D4144FF3C262C4B29FE4F" blockId="7.[151,1437,284,635]" pageId="7" pageNumber="408">
<emphasis id="C4E46401FF9D4144FF3C262C4B5EFE92" bold="true" box="[151,274,284,310]" pageId="7" pageNumber="408">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="3190C390FF9D4144FEB2262C4B92FE92" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1853" box="[281,478,284,310]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="408" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dicax">
<emphasis id="C4E46401FF9D4144FEB2262C4B92FE92" box="[281,478,284,310]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="408">Ascalaphus dicax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished by the angled antenna at the proximal region in the male, with short black setae on basal flagellomeres, while straight in female. Although this species shows similarities with the other two congeners known from 
<collectingCountry id="8E87F883FF9D4144FD9C265448D5FEDA" box="[567,665,356,382]" name="Pakistan" pageId="7" pageNumber="408">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
, it can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="3190C390FF9D4144FC7426554ED5FEDA" baseAuthorityName="Kimmins" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[991,1177,356,383]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="408" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prothoracicus">
<emphasis id="C4E46401FF9D4144FC7426554ED5FEDA" box="[991,1177,356,383]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="408">A. prothoracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to the absence of a well-developed triangular process on the mesonotum which is present in 
<taxonomicName id="3190C390FF9D4144FC6A26B94E37FE06" baseAuthorityName="Kimmins" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[961,1147,392,419]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="408" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prothoracicus">
<emphasis id="C4E46401FF9D4144FC6A26B94E37FE06" box="[961,1147,392,419]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="408">A. prothoracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and from 
<taxonomicName id="3190C390FF9D4144FB5826B94FD0FE06" baseAuthorityName="Kimmins" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[1267,1436,392,419]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="408" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abdominalis">
<emphasis id="C4E46401FF9D4144FB5826B94FD0FE06" box="[1267,1436,392,419]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="408">A. abdominalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to lack of well-develpoed median dilation on the lateral margin of abdominal tergum 4, which is well-developed in 
<taxonomicName id="3190C390FF9D4144FF1F26E14B11FE4E" baseAuthorityName="Kimmins" baseAuthorityYear="1949" box="[180,349,464,491]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ascalaphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="408" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abdominalis">
<emphasis id="C4E46401FF9D4144FF1F26E14B11FE4E" box="[180,349,464,491]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="408">A. abdominalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
